1. Purpose

The Combat Mapping Library (CML) defines the transformation rules between abstract chess events and cinematic combat actions.

The library provides the vocabulary required for the Cinematic Engine to translate:

Chess Intelligence
        |
        v
Chess Event
        |
        v
Combat Mapping Library
        |
        v
Cinematic Action

Example:

Input:

Knight captures bishop

Output:

Knight performs aerial assassination combo
2. Design Philosophy

The Combat Mapping Library follows three principles:

2.1 Preserve Chess Meaning

A cinematic action must represent the strategic meaning of the move.

Example:

A knight fork is not simply an attack.

It represents:

surprise
tactical superiority
multi-target pressure

Therefore:

Knight Fork
      |
      v
Assassin Combo Attack
2.2 Preserve Piece Identity

Every chess piece has a unique combat personality.

A queen attack and pawn attack should never feel identical.

2.3 Allow Multiple Interpretations

The same chess event can produce different cinematic outcomes.

Example:

Queen capture:

Possible outputs:

Dominance:

Queen destroys enemy instantly

or:

Revenge:

Queen eliminates the enemy after taking damage
